They were terrified that the evacuees would bring the new plague into their villages, and they responded with violence.
This incident was just one of many discussed during a March 12 meeting about racism and coronavirus at the London School of Hygiene.
Around the world, as the pandemic spreads, the terror associated with this unknown disease has become a petri dish for the rise of intolerance and a broader epidemic of violence.
Down the line, regaining our civil rights and freedoms at the back end of a pandemic will be a huge struggle.
As ever, grassroots activism will be essential in pushing for the liberties that should be guaranteed to all.